\f0\b\fs28 \cf0 \CocoaLigature0 The Square \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  \'97 A Tekmerion
\f1\b0 \

\f0\b The Earliest Attestation: Simonides of Ceos (c. 556\'96468 BCE)
\f1\b0 \
The metaphor originates in a poem addressed to Scopas of Thessaly, preserved within\'a0
\f0\b Plato's
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i Protagoras
\f1\i0 :\

\f0\b Plato,
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i Protagoras
\f1\i0 \'a0
\f0\b (Eulogikon: ffk-al, Prot.362.a):
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u7940 \u957 \u948 \u961 ' \u7936 \u947 \u945 \u952 \u8056 \u957  \u956 \u8050 \u957  \u7936 \u955 \u945 \u952 \u941 \u969 \u962  \u947 \u949 \u957 \u941 \u963 \u952 \u945 \u953  \u967 \u945 \u955 \u949 \u960 \u972 \u957 , \u967 \u949 \u961 \u963 \u943 \u957  \u964 \u949  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u960 \u959 \u963 \u8054  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u957 \u972 \u8179  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u957 , \u7940 \u957 \u949 \u965  \u968 \u972 \u947 \u959 \u965  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u965 \u947 \u956 \u941 \u957 \u959 \u957 .
\f1\b0 \
"A truly good man it is hard to become,\'a0
\f0\b square in hands and feet and \uc0\u957 \u959 \u8166 \u962 , fashioned without blame
\f1\b0 ."\
Three observations:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\fs24 \cf0 \CocoaLigature1 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\fs28 \CocoaLigature0 The square is applied to the\'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u7936 \u957 \u942 \u961 
\f1\b0 \'a0(man), not yet to \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 .\
\ls1\ilvl0
\fs24 \CocoaLigature1 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\fs28 \CocoaLigature0 The domains are threefold \'97 hands (action), feet (movement), \uc0\u957 \u959 \u8166 \u962  (intellect) \'97 covering the whole person.\
\ls1\ilvl0
\fs24 \CocoaLigature1 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}
\fs28 \CocoaLigature0 The context is a rejection of Pittacus' dictum: Simonides says\'a0
\f2\i becoming
\f1\i0 \'a0good is hard,\'a0
\f2\i remaining
\f1\i0 \'a0good is for a god alone. The square denotes stable character that withstands fortune.\
\pard\tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\uc0\u10240 Plato's Socrates then analyses this poem line by line, making it the centrepiece of a debate on whether \u7936 \u961 \u949 \u964 \u942  can be taught. The square man becomes a philosophical problem.\
\

\f0\b Aristotle (384\'96322 BCE) \'97 The Ethical Application
\f1\b0 \
Aristotle takes the Simonidean phrase and applies it to the\'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u949 \u8016 \u948 \u945 \u943 \u956 \u969 \u957 
\f1\b0 :\

\f0\b Aristotle,
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i Nicomachean Ethics
\f1\i0 \'a0
\f0\b (Eulogikon: hgw-aw, EN 1100b):
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u954 \u945 \u8054  \u964 \u8048 \u962  \u964 \u973 \u967 \u945 \u962  \u959 \u7988 \u963 \u949 \u953  \u954 \u940 \u955 \u955 \u953 \u963 \u964 \u945  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u960 \u940 \u957 \u964 \u8131  \u960 \u940 \u957 \u964 \u969 \u962  \u7952 \u956 \u956 \u949 \u955 \u8182 \u962  \u8005  \u947 ' \u8033 \u962  \u7936 \u955 \u951 \u952 \u8182 \u962  \u7936 \u947 \u945 \u952 \u8056 \u962  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u962  \u7940 \u957 \u949 \u965  \u968 \u972 \u947 \u959 \u965 .
\f1\b0 \
"And he will bear his fortunes most beautifully and in every way harmoniously \'97\'a0
\f0\b the man who is truly good and square, without blame
\f1\b0 ."\
Aristotle's innovation: the square is now explicitly a disposition toward\'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u964 \u973 \u967 \u951 
\f1\b0 \'a0(fortune). The stable man, like a square block, stands firm no matter which side it falls on.\
\

\f0\b Aspasius (c. 100\'96150 CE) \'97 The First Explicit Commentary
\f1\b0 \
The Peripatetic commentator\'a0
\f0\b Aspasius
\f1\b0 \'a0gives the fullest ancient gloss:\

\f0\b Aspasius,
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i Commentary on Aristotle's Nicomachean Ethics
\f1\i0 \'a0
\f0\b (Eulogikon: pms-aa, 29):
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u959 \u7985  \u956 \u8050 \u957  \u947 \u8048 \u961  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u953  \u955 \u941 \u947 \u959 \u957 \u964 \u945 \u953  \u959 \u7985  \u963 \u965 \u956 \u956 \u949 \u964 \u945 \u964 \u953 \u952 \u941 \u956 \u949 \u957 \u959 \u953  \u964 \u959 \u8150 \u962  \u7972 \u952 \u949 \u963 \u953  \u964 \u8182 \u957  \u963 \u965 \u947 \u947 \u953 \u957 \u959 \u956 \u941 \u957 \u969 \u957 \'85 \u959 \u8023 \u964 \u959 \u953  \u956 \u8050 \u957  \u948 \u8052  \u7952 \u960 \u943 \u968 \u959 \u947 \u959 \u953 \'b7 \u7940 \u957 \u949 \u965  \u948 \u8050  \u968 \u972 \u947 \u959 \u965  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u953  \u959 \u7985  \u964 \u8048 \u962  \u964 \u973 \u967 \u945 \u962  \u7952 \u956 \u956 \u949 \u955 \u8182 \u962  \u966 \u941 \u961 \u959 \u957 \u964 \u949 \u962  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u956 \u942 \u964 \u949  \u8017 \u960 \u8056  \u948 \u965 \u963 \u964 \u965 \u967 \u943 \u945 \u962  \u954 \u945 \u964 \u945 \u960 \u943 \u960 \u964 \u959 \u957 \u964 \u949 \u962  \u956 \u942 \u964 \u949  \u8017 \u960 \u8056  \u949 \u8016 \u964 \u965 \u967 \u943 \u945 \u962  \u7952 \u960 \u945 \u953 \u961 \u972 \u956 \u949 \u957 \u959 \u953 , \u7936 \u955 \u955 ' \u8037 \u963 \u960 \u949 \u961  \u959 \u7985  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u953  \u955 \u943 \u952 \u959 \u953  \u7952 \u966 ' \u8003  \u7938 \u957  \u960 \u941 \u963 \u969 \u963 \u953  \u956 \u941 \u961 \u959 \u962  \u7953 \u963 \u964 \u8118 \u963 \u953 \u957 , \u959 \u8021 \u964 \u969 \u962  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u959 \u8023 \u964 \u959 \u953  \u954 \u945 \u964 \u8048  \u960 \u8118 \u963 \u945 \u957  \u964 \u973 \u967 \u951 \u957  \u7953 \u963 \u964 \u942 \u954 \u945 \u963 \u953 \u957  \u8000 \u961 \u952 \u959 \u943 .
\f1\b0 \
"For some are called 'square' who adapt themselves to the characters of those they associate with\'85 These are blameworthy. But\'a0
\f0\b 'square without blame'
\f1\b0 \'a0are those who bear fortunes harmoniously, neither collapsing under misfortune nor being elated by good fortune, but\'a0
\f0\b just as square stones stand firm on whatever side they fall, so these men stand upright in every fortune
\f1\b0 ."\
Aspasius distinguishes two senses: (1) a\'a0
\f2\i negative
\f1\i0 \'a0sense of the chameleon-like person (blameworthy), and (2) the\'a0
\f2\i positive
\f1\i0 \'a0Aristotelian sense of the man whose character is so stable that fortune cannot topple him. The key image is the\'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u962  \u955 \u943 \u952 \u959 \u962 
\f1\b0 \'a0(square stone).\
\

\f0\b The Pythagorean Tradition \'97 The \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  as a Square
\f1\b0 \
A separate strand identifies the\'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  itself
\f1\b0 \'a0as a square. Attributed to\'a0
\f0\b Pythagoras
\f1\b0 \'a0by later doxographers:\

\f0\b John the Lydian,
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i On the Months
\f1\i0 \'a0
\f0\b (Eulogikon: vhw-ab, Mens 2.9):
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u964 \u8048  \u947 \u8048 \u961  \u964 \u8134 \u962  \u968 \u965 \u967 \u8134 \u962  \u963 \u964 \u951 \u961 \u943 \u947 \u956 \u945 \u964 \u945  \u964 \u941 \u963 \u963 \u945 \u961 \u940  \u7952 \u963 \u964 \u953 , \u957 \u959 \u8166 \u962  \u7952 \u960 \u953 \u963 \u964 \u942 \u956 \u951  \u948 \u972 \u958 \u945  \u945 \u7988 \u963 \u952 \u951 \u963 \u953 \u962 . \u968 \u965 \u967 \u8048  \u947 \u8048 \u961  \u7936 \u957 \u952 \u961 \u974 \u960 \u959 \u965 , \u8033 \u962  \u928 \u965 \u952 \u945 \u947 \u972 \u961 \u945 \u962  \u7956 \u966 \u951 , \u7956 \u963 \u964 \u953  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u957  \u8000 \u961 \u952 \u959 \u947 \u974 \u957 \u953 \u959 \u957 .
\f1\b0 \
"For the\'a0
\f0\b supports of the \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  are four: \u957 \u959 \u8166 \u962 , \u7952 \u960 \u953 \u963 \u964 \u942 \u956 \u951 , \u948 \u972 \u958 \u945 , \u945 \u7988 \u963 \u952 \u951 \u963 \u953 \u962 
\f1\b0 . For the \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  of a human being,\'a0
\f0\b as Pythagoras said, is a right-angled square
\f1\b0 ."\
The same attribution appears in\'a0
\f0\b Pseudo-Archytas
\f1\b0 \'a0(Eulogikon: mxk-aa, 47) and the\'a0
\f0\b Pythagoras fragments
\f1\b0 \'a0(Eulogikon: bgs-ae, 165). John the Lydian connects this to the tetrad and the four pillars of the \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 . The square \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  is stable, balanced, and proportioned \'97 a mathematical expression of psychic harmony.\
\

\f0\b Proclus (412\'96485 CE) \'97 The Neoplatonic Synthesis
\f1\b0 \

\f0\b Proclus
\f1\b0 , commenting on Plato's\'a0
\f2\i Timaeus
\f1\i0 , integrates the square into the \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 's numerical structure:\

\f0\b Proclus,
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i Commentary on Plato's Timaeus
\f1\i0 \'a0
\f0\b (Eulogikon: uqy-ah, in Ti.2.271):
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u960 \u940 \u957 \u964 \u969 \u962  \u7940 \u961 \u945  \u959 \u7985  \u7936 \u961 \u953 \u952 \u956 \u959 \u8054  \u960 \u940 \u957 \u964 \u949 \u962  \u949 \u7984 \u963 \u8054  \u964 \u8135  \u959 \u8016 \u963 \u943 \u8115  \u964 \u8134 \u962  \u968 \u965 \u967 \u8134 \u962 , \u956 \u959 \u957 \u940 \u962 , \u948 \u965 \u940 \u962 , \u964 \u961 \u953 \u940 \u962 , \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u962 , \u960 \u949 \u957 \u964 \u940 \u962 , \u7953 \u958 \u940 \u962 , \u7953 \u960 \u964 \u940 \u962 , \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u7952 \u960 \u8054  \u960 \u8118 \u963 \u953 \u957  \u8001  \u7936 \u960 \u8056  \u964 \u8134 \u962  \u7953 \u960 \u964 \u940 \u948 \u959 \u962  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u962 .
\f1\b0 \
"All numbers are therefore in the \uc0\u959 \u8016 \u963 \u943 \u945  of the \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 : monad, dyad, triad, tetrad, pentad, hexad, heptad,\'a0
\f0\b and above all the square from the heptad
\f1\b0 ."\
Here the square (49 = 7\'b2) is the culminating number in the \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 's structure \'97 the product of the hebdomad, linked to the World \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 's division in the\'a0
\f2\i Timaeus
\f1\i0 .\
\

\f0\b The Four Elements and the Tetrad \'97 Theon of Smyrna
\f1\b0 \

\f0\b Theon of Smyrna
\f1\b0 \'a0(c. 70\'96135 CE) gives the most systematic synthesis of Pythagorean tetrads:\

\f0\b Theon of Smyrna,
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i On the Usefulness of Mathematics
\f1\i0 \'a0
\f0\b (Eulogikon: pic-aa, 97\'9698):
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u932 \u949 \u964 \u940 \u961 \u964 \u951  \u948 \u8050  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u945 \u954 \u964 \u973 \u962  \u7952 \u963 \u964 \u953  \u964 \u8182 \u957  \u7937 \u960 \u955 \u8182 \u957  \u963 \u969 \u956 \u940 \u964 \u969 \u957 , \u960 \u965 \u961 \u8056 \u962  \u7936 \u941 \u961 \u959 \u962  \u8021 \u948 \u945 \u964 \u959 \u962  \u947 \u8134 \u962 \'85 \u928 \u941 \u956 \u960 \u964 \u951  \u948 ' \u7952 \u963 \u964 \u8054  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u945 \u954 \u964 \u8058 \u962  \u7969  \u964 \u8182 \u957  \u963 \u967 \u951 \u956 \u940 \u964 \u969 \u957  \u964 \u8182 \u957  \u7937 \u960 \u955 \u8182 \u957  \u963 \u969 \u956 \u940 \u964 \u969 \u957 . \u7969  \u956 \u8050 \u957  \u947 \u8048 \u961  \u960 \u965 \u961 \u945 \u956 \u8054 \u962  \u963 \u967 \u8134 \u956 \u945  \u960 \u965 \u961 \u972 \u962 , \u964 \u8056  \u948 \u8050  \u8000 \u954 \u964 \u940 \u949 \u948 \u961 \u959 \u957  \u7936 \u941 \u961 \u959 \u962 , \u964 \u8056  \u948 \u8050  \u949 \u7984 \u954 \u959 \u963 \u940 \u949 \u948 \u961 \u959 \u957  \u8021 \u948 \u945 \u964 \u959 \u962 , \u954 \u973 \u946 \u959 \u962  \u948 \u8050  \u947 \u8134 \u962 .
\f1\b0 \
"The\'a0
\f0\b fourth tetrad
\f1\b0 \'a0is of the simple bodies:\'a0
\f0\b fire, air, water, earth
\f1\b0 \'85 The\'a0
\f0\b fifth tetrad
\f1\b0 \'a0is of the shapes of the simple bodies: the pyramid is the shape of fire, the octahedron of air, the icosahedron of water, the\'a0
\f0\b cube of earth
\f1\b0 ."\
Then the tetrad of the \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 's faculties:\

\f0\b \uc0\u8000 \u947 \u948 \u972 \u951  \u948 \u8050  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u945 \u954 \u964 \u8058 \u962  \u7973 \u948 \u949 , \u964 \u959 \u973 \u964 \u969 \u957  \u954 \u961 \u953 \u964 \u953 \u954 \u8052  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u957 \u959 \u951 \u964 \u942  \u964 \u953 \u962  \u959 \u8022 \u963 \u945 \'b7 \u957 \u959 \u8166 \u962  \u7952 \u960 \u953 \u963 \u964 \u942 \u956 \u951  \u948 \u972 \u958 \u945  \u945 \u7988 \u963 \u952 \u951 \u963 \u953 \u962 .
\f1\b0 \
"The\'a0
\f0\b eighth tetrad
\f1\b0 \'a0is critical and intelligible:\'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u957 \u959 \u8166 \u962 , \u7952 \u960 \u953 \u963 \u964 \u942 \u956 \u951 , \u948 \u972 \u958 \u945 , \u945 \u7988 \u963 \u952 \u951 \u963 \u953 \u962 
\f1\b0 ."\
The number-four structure runs from the four \uc0\u963 \u964 \u959 \u953 \u967 \u949 \u8150 \u945  through the four Platonic solids (with the cube = \u947 \u8134  = earth) through the four cognitive faculties to the tripartite \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  + body.\
\

\f0\b Late Antique Usage \'97 The Ethical Ideal
\f1\b0 \
The phrase\'a0
\f0\b \'ab\uc0\u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u962  \u7940 \u957 \u949 \u965  \u968 \u972 \u947 \u959 \u965 \'bb
\f1\b0 \'a0became proverbial.\'a0
\f0\b Julian the Apostate
\f1\b0 :\

\f0\b Julian,
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i Symposium or Kronia
\f1\i0 \'a0
\f0\b (Eulogikon: sno-am, 38):
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u916 \u959 \u954 \u949 \u8150  \u947 \u8048 \u961  \u949 \u7990 \u957 \u945 \u943  \u956 \u959 \u943  \u960 \u969 \u962  \u7936 \u957 \u8052 \u961  \u954 \u945 \u964 \u8048  \u964 \u8056 \u957  \u931 \u953 \u956 \u969 \u957 \u943 \u948 \u951 \u957  \'ab\u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u962  \u7940 \u957 \u949 \u965  \u968 \u972 \u947 \u959 \u965  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u965 \u947 \u956 \u941 \u957 \u959 \u962 .\'bb
\f1\b0 \
"For he seems to me to be a man, in Simonides' words,\'a0
\f0\b 'square, fashioned without blame.'
\f1\b0 "\
And\'a0
\f0\b Damascius
\f1\b0 \'a0applies it to the philosopher Isidore:\

\f0\b Damascius,
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f2\i Life of Isidore
\f1\i0 \'a0
\f0\b (Eulogikon: uyg-ab, 332):
\f1\b0 \'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u963 \u949 \u956 \u957 \u8056 \u962  \u948 \u8050  \u7974 \u957  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u949 \u8016 \u963 \u967 \u942 \u956 \u969 \u957  \u964 \u8048  \u960 \u940 \u957 \u964 \u945  \u954 \u945 \u8054  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u962  \u7940 \u957 \u949 \u965  \u968 \u972 \u947 \u959 \u965  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u945 \u947 \u956 \u941 \u957 \u959 \u962 , \u8033 \u962  \u966 \u940 \u957 \u945 \u953  \u954 \u945 \u964 \u8048  \u964 \u8056 \u957  \u931 \u953 \u956 \u969 \u957 \u943 \u948 \u951 \u957 .
\f1\b0 \
"He was dignified and well-formed in all things and\'a0
\f0\b ordered square without blame
\f1\b0 , as one might say in Simonides' words."\
\

