\f0\b The Four \uc0\u931 \u964 \u959 \u953 \u967 \u949 \u8150 \u945  Connection
\f1\b0 \
The link between the square \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  and the four elements runs through the\'a0
\f0\b architecture of the tetrad
\f1\b0 :\

\f0\b 1
\f1\b0  
\f0\b The tetraktys
\f1\b0 \'a0(1, 2, 3, 4 = 10) is the root of all things \'97 the oldest Pythagorean doctrine.\
2 The\'a0
\f0\b four \uc0\u963 \u964 \u959 \u953 \u967 \u949 \u8150 \u945 
\f1\b0 \'a0are one application of the tetrad (Theon's fourth tetrad: \uc0\u960 \u8166 \u961 , \u7936 \u942 \u961 , \u8021 \u948 \u969 \u961 , \u947 \u8134 ).\
3 The\'a0
\f0\b four cognitive faculties
\f1\b0 \'a0(\uc0\u957 \u959 \u8166 \u962 , \u7952 \u960 \u953 \u963 \u964 \u942 \u956 \u951 , \u948 \u972 \u958 \u945 , \u945 \u7988 \u963 \u952 \u951 \u963 \u953 \u962 ) are another application (Theon's eighth tetrad).\
4 The\'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  as a square
\f1\b0 \'a0(\uc0\u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u957  \u949 \u8016 \u952 \u965 \u947 \u974 \u957 \u953 \u959 \u957 ) is the geometric expression of this tetradic structure.\
5 The\'a0
\f0\b four Platonic solids
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 with the cube (\uc0\u954 \u973 \u946 \u959 \u962 ) corresponding to earth \'97 provide the geometrical bridge: just as square faces compose the cube, so the square \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  is the principle that structures the physical world.\
\
\uc0\u10240 The\'a0
\f0\b cube = \uc0\u947 \u8134 
\f1\b0 \'a0(earth) is the third dimension of the square \'97 the square made solid. And Theon's ninth tetrad explicitly links the tripartite \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  (\u955 \u959 \u947 \u953 \u963 \u964 \u953 \u954 \u972 \u957 , \u952 \u965 \u956 \u953 \u954 \u972 \u957 , \u7952 \u960 \u953 \u952 \u965 \u956 \u951 \u964 \u953 \u954 \u972 \u957 ) to the \u963 \u8182 \u956 \u945  as a fourth term \'97 making the embodied \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  a\'a0
\f0\b fourfold structure
\f1\b0 \'a0that maps onto the four-element cosmos.\
\

\f0\b Caveats and Open Questions
\f1\b0 \

\f0\b 1
\f1\b0  
\f0\b The exact phrase \'ab\uc0\u7969  \u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u962  \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 \'bb is not attested
\f1\b0 \'a0in the Eulogikon corpus. The \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  is always called\'a0
\f0\b \uc0\u964 \u949 \u964 \u961 \u940 \u947 \u969 \u957 \u959 \u957 
\f1\b0 \'a0(neuter) \'97 "a square" \'97 not "the square \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 ." The feminine collocation may be a modern scholarly shorthand.\

\f0\b 2
\f1\b0  
\f0\b The Pythagorean attribution
\f1\b0 \'a0is doxographical. John the Lydian and Pseudo-Archytas write centuries after Pythagoras; the saying may be a retrojection of later mathematical psychology onto the founder.\

\f0\b 3
\f1\b0  
\f0\b The corpus does not contain
\f1\b0 \'a0the relevant passage from\'a0
\f0\b Plutarch
\f1\b0 \'a0(who discusses the square \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  in\'a0
\f2\i De virtute morali
\f1\i0 \'a0or elsewhere) \'97 this would be valuable for a fuller picture.\

\f0\b 4
\f1\b0  
\f0\b The four cardinal virtues
\f1\b0 \'a0(\uc0\u966 \u961 \u972 \u957 \u951 \u963 \u953 \u962 , \u963 \u969 \u966 \u961 \u959 \u963 \u973 \u957 \u951 , \u7936 \u957 \u948 \u961 \u949 \u943 \u945 , \u948 \u953 \u954 \u945 \u953 \u959 \u963 \u973 \u957 \u951 ) are never explicitly mapped onto the four sides of the square in the corpus. The Pythagorean tradition uses a\'a0
\f2\i different
\f1\i0 \'a0tetrad (\uc0\u957 \u959 \u8166 \u962 , \u7952 \u960 \u953 \u963 \u964 \u942 \u956 \u951 , \u948 \u972 \u958 \u945 , \u945 \u7988 \u963 \u952 \u951 \u963 \u953 \u962 ). The connection to the virtues is indirect, via the number 4 and Anatolius's identification of the tetrad with \u948 \u953 \u954 \u945 \u953 \u959 \u963 \u973 \u957 \u951  (Eulogikon: uak-aa, 7).\

\f0\b 5
\f1\b0  
\f0\b What would settle the question
\f1\b0 \'a0of whether the original Pythagorean oral teaching already connected the square \uc0\u968 \u965 \u967 \u942  to the four elements: a pre-Platonic Pythagorean text that makes the link explicitly. None survives; the earliest attestation is Simonides (who does not mention \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 ), and the \u968 \u965 \u967 \u942 -as-square is first attested in late doxography claiming to transmit oral teaching.\
